STA141B Code Report¶

Introduction¶

The Davis Labor Day Running Races stand as an important annual event, attracting participants with its athleticism and community spirit. This code report will provide the analysis of data associated with these races, finding valuable insights and patterns within the information. By employing web scraping techniques, we gather data directly from the event's official website, ensuring accuracy and up-to-date information for our analysis.

Our scraping website can be found at this link.

Methodology¶

To construct our dataset, we employ web scraping using Python, utilize libraries such as BeautifulSoup and requests. The script navigates through the structure of the Davis Labor Day Running Races website, extracting information such as participant names, participant age, time the participant spent to finish the race, gender, race type(5K/10K), and year of the race held. Once gathered, the data is organized and transformed into a structured CSV file, ensuring accessibility for subsequent analysis. This approach allows us to automate the data retrieval process, facilitating efficiency for future analysis by avoiding rescraping the data from the website. The analysis section of this report will delve into the exploratory data analysis and plots derived from the acquired dataset and provide readers with the performance and trends observed in the Davis Labor Day Running Races. (For the code of scraping, see appendix)

Our processed data can be found at this link.

Getter (helper) Functions Implementations¶

This chunk of code consists of helper functions that return our desired value from the table in the website. For example, participant's name, age, and finish time, ect. There will be a construct function that generates dataframe by calling these helper functions. By observed, all helper functions require response as argument, and some of them expect year.

Here is how each helper funciton work¶

  1. Convert the response (HTML file) into a Beautiful Soup object.
  2. Find all the matching values by using find_all() function from the html file. Matched values are the texts in the html file that we are interested in
    • We identify the tag and class of the desired texts using Chrome's developer tools, and then specify them in the function to obtain our result.
  3. For each value in the list of matched values
    • Extract the content by using beautiful soup object's get_text() function
    • Append the content to a list
  4. After we have a list of content, convert the list to pandas series object
  5. Filter out irrelevant content from the dataframe. Irrelevant information were captured because they share the same tag and class in the html file, and were captured in step 2 where we used find_all() function.
    • We observe the pattern of occurrence for the desired contents, and for each type of information (age, finish time, etc.), the patterns are different. More details about this are provided below.
    • The same information in different years might be rendered differently, so some helper functions take the year as a parameter to extract the desired content accordingly.
  6. Reset the index
  7. Return the series

Problems faced and solutions¶

During the process of data scraping, when we test the dataframe we got from the website, we ended with result like this:

Name Age
Lisa Geibel-Finn 744
Christopher Kim 799
Carey Seal 758
Lenna Ontai 655

Apparently, we didn't manage to capture the correct age values. There must be something wrong in the process of extracting desired age values. The thing that causes confusion is that the method we used in page 2 worked with no trouble, so we then observed the difference of the tables between 2 pages.

After observation, we found that there is a column named Sp Div Pos(stands for "Special Division Position") that share the same tag and class as the texts containing our desired age values. On the table from page 2, there is no value under this column, and in contrast, some of rows contain value under this column on the table from page 3. The occurence of the first value of Sp Div Pos ruins the pattern that "each age value is separated by 3 irrevelant values to the next age value", as the first Sp Div Pos value make the distance from 3 to 4. As a result, all the following data were captured incorrectly.

We then considered to eliminate the html text with the occurence of Sp Div Pos value, but since they share the exact same tag and class as the age value as mentioned serveral times above, we were not able to find a way to do that.

We spent hours to find a way to eliminate the html text with the occurence of Sp Div Pos value, but none of the apporaches worked. We then started over, and observed the captured html texts from find_all() function (the output from the line of code above is an example, where 67 is the first age value). We noticed that the third line contains no value, which is the NA that we dropped after converting the html texts to pandas series.

We then realized that dropping the NA value is a wrong decision since they are the values under the Sp Div Pos column. If the participant is not in any special division (Stroller Division, Dog Division, ect), the value in the participant's row under column Sp Div Pos will be a blank, which is the third line in the output above, and which is also the NA we dropped previously.

Once the first Sp Div Pos value occured, it means that one more irrevelant value appears between two age values since it's not a NA, and we didn't drop it.

The simplest way to fix it is that not to drop NA, instead, change the pattern that we extract the age values.

Name Age
Lisa Geibel-Finn 58
Christopher Kim 53
Carey Seal 42
Lenna Ontai 50

Now we have sovled the problem! The names and ages match.
